r-gop-congressman-lands-lucrative-lobbying-gig-n874101|title=Disgraced former GOP congressman lands lucrative lobbying gig|work=NBC News|access-date=May 15, 2018|language=en-US}}</ref> A member of the [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican Party]], Farenthold co-hosted a conservative talk radio program before he began his political career. Farenthold served as the [[United States House of Representatives|U.S. Representative]] for {{ushr|TX|27}} from 2011 until his resignation in April 2018 in the wake of reports he used public funds to settle a sexual harassment lawsuit and had created an intensely hostile work environment for women in his congressional office.<ref name=\"Politico-2017-12-01\">{{cite news | last1=Bade | first1=Rachael | title=Lawmaker behind secret $84K sexual harassment settlement unmasked | url=https://www.politico.com/story/2017/12/01/blake-farenthold-taxpayer-funds-sexual-harassment-274458 | date=December 1, 2017 | publisher=Politico}}</ref><ref name=\"twsNYT01\">The New York Times, YAMICHE ALCINDOR and SHERYL GAY STOLBERG, December 1, 2017, [https://www.nytimes.com/2017/12/01/us/politics/farenthold-sexual-harassement-settlement-taxpayers-congress.html?smid=fb-share&_r=0 Taxpayers Paid $84,000 to End Sex Harassment Claim Against Texas Lawmaker], Retrieved December 3, 2017, \"...In 2014, the congressman's former communications director, Lauren Greene, accused him of regularly making comments to gauge her interest in a sexual relationship....Farenthold of drinking \"to excess\" on numerous occasions...\"</ref><ref name=\":2\" /><ref name=\":3\" /> Upon resigning, Farenthold pledged to reimburse the [[US$]]84,000 in public money that he used to settle the lawsuit, then reneged his pledge to repay in May 2018.<ref name=\":1\" /><ref name=\"WaPo reimburse\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/powerpost/wp/2018/05/15/ex-rep-farenthold-says-he-wont-repay-84k-sexual-harassment-settlement/ |title=Ex-Rep. Farenthold says he won't repay $84K sexual harassment settlement |last=Viebeck |first=Elise |date=May 15, 2018 |website=[[Washington Post]] |language=en-US |quote='I will say this on the record: I have been advised by my attorneys not to repay that,' Farenthold told [ABC News]. 'That's why it hasn't been repaid.'|access-date=June 11, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Early life and education==\nFarenthold was born and raised in [[Corpus Christi, Texas|Corpus Christi]], Texas, the son of Mary Sue (n\u00e9e Ogg) and George Randolph \"Randy\" Farenthold. His wealthy paternal grandfather, George Edward Farenthold, was a [[Belgian]] immigrant who was the descendant of an aristocratic industrialist family and worked in the oil industry in Texas<ref name=\"BloodOfFarentholds\">{{cite magazine|last=Draper|first=Robert|title=The Blood of the Farentholds|url=https://www.texasmonthly.com/articles/the-blood-of-the-farentholds|accessdate=October 20, 2013|magazine=Texas Monthly|date=April 1992}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://freepages.genealogy.rootsweb.ancestry.com/~battle/reps/farenthold.htm|title=Blake Farenthold ancestry|website=ancestry.com|accessdate=July 7, 2017}}</ref> and he is the former step-grandson of [[Sissy Farenthold]] who married and divorced his grandfather, George Farenthold.<ref name=\"BloodOfFarentholds\" />\n\nFarenthold attended [[Incarnate Word Academy (Corpus Christi, Texas)|Incarnate Word Academy]] and the [[University of Texas at Austin]] where he received a B.S. degree in Radio, Television, and Film. He received a [[Juris Doctor|J.D.]] degree from [[St. Mary's University School of Law]] in San Antonio,<ref name=\"Blake Farenthold Campaign Website\">[http://blakefarenthold.com/about/ Blake Farenthold Campaign Website] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101104200714/http://blakefarenthold.com/about|date=November 4, 2010}}</ref> and was admitted to the Texas Bar (Bar# 06814500).\n\n==Early career==\nFarenthold's pre-political career includes working as a radio disc jockey in high school and college, seven years of practicing law at the Kleberg Law Firm in [[Corpus Christi, TX|Corpus Christi]], and founding Farenthold Consulting LLC, a computer consulting and web design firm.\n\nFarenthold co-hosted ''Lago in the Morning,'' a conservative [[talk radio]] program on [[KKTX (AM)|KKTX]] radio until he began his political campaign.\n\n==U.S. House of Representatives==\n\n===Elections===\n;2010\n{{See also|United States House of Representatives elections in Texas, 2010#District 27}}\nFarenthold defeated [[incumbent]] [[Democratic Party (US)|Democratic]] Rep. [[Solomon Ortiz]] by 799 votes on election night.<ref name=\"Corpus Christi Caller Times\">[http://www.caller.com/news/2010/nov/03/farenthold-ousts-ortiz-in-tight-race-n-deck/ Farenthold Ousts Ortiz in Tight Race], Accessed on November 3, 2010</ref> Ortiz asked for a manual recount. On Monday, November 22, Ortiz conceded the race to Farenthold. Farenthold's final margin of victory over Ortiz was 47.85 to 47.1 percent.<ref name=TXSOS10>{{cite news | title = 2010 General Election, Election Night Returns, Unofficial Elections Results As Of: 11/3/2010 12:14:58 PM | date = November 3, 2010 | url = http://elections.sos.state.tx.us/elchist154_state.htm | work = Texas Secretary of State | accessdate = February 10, 2016|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160203101055/http://elections.sos.state.tx.us/elchist154_state.htm|archive-date=February 3, 2016}}</ref> His margin of victory was 799 votes.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2014/03/22/bill-maher-flip-a-district_n_5013348.html |title=Bill Maher's Campaign To Find The Worst Member Of Congress Is Underway|author=Chris Gentilviso|publisher=''[[The Huffington Post]]''|date=March 23, 2014|accessdate=January 2, 2015}}</ref> Ortiz had represented the district since its creation in 1982.\n\n;2012\n{{See also|United States House of Representatives elections in Texas, 2012#District 27}}\n[[Redistricting]] after the 2010 census made Farenthold's district significantly more Republican. His old district had been 70 percent Latino, but the new map shifted most of the Latino areas to the newly created 34th district.  To make up for the loss in population, his district was shifted well to the north and east, absorbing some heavily Republican territory near [[Houston, Texas|Houston]] and [[Austin, Texas|Austin]].\n\nHe defeated Democratic nominee Rose Meza Harrison 57-39 percent.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://elections.sos.state.tx.us/elchist.exe |title=Archived copy |accessdate=March 19, 2014 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20061108172637/http://elections.sos.state.tx.us/elchist.exe |archivedate=November 8, 2006 |df= }}</ref>\n\n;2014\n{{See also|United States House of Representatives elections in Texas, 2014#District 27}}\nFarenthold was not challenged in the Republican primary. In the general election, he defeated Democrat Wesley Reed by a margin of 83,342 to 44,152 (63.6% to 33.7%).<ref>{{cite news|last1=Hendricks|first1=Dave|title=Farenthold retains congressional seat|url=http://www.caller.com/news/politics/national/farenthold-takes-commanding-lead-in-early-voting_26305095|accessdate=December 17, 2014|work=Corpus Christie Caller Times |date=November 4, 2014}}</ref>\n[[File:Blake Farenthold 2015.jpg|thumb|Farenthold's official portrait for the 114th session]]\n\n;2016\n{{See also|United States House of Representatives elections in Texas, 2016#District 27}}\nFarenthold won re-nomination in the March 1 Republican primary with 42,872 votes (56 percent) to 33,699 (44 percent) for his challenger, Gregg Patrick Deeb (born c. 1964) of Corpus Christi, who formerly lived in [[South Carolina]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://enrpages.sos.state.tx.us/public/mar01_273_state.htm?x=0&y=3943&id=252|title=Republican primary returns|date=March 1, 2016 |publisher=Texas Secretary of State|accessdate=March 4, 2016|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160306144031/https://enrpages.sos.state.tx.us/public/mar01_273_state.htm?x=0&y=3943&id=252|archivedate=March 6, 2016|df=}}</ref> In the general election held on November 8, Farenthold defeated the Democrat Raul \"Roy\" Barrera, who had won his party nomination on March 1 with 16,140 votes (50.3 percent) over two opponents.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://enrpages.sos.state.tx.us/public/mar01_233_state.htm |title=Democratic primary returns |date=March 1, 2016 |publisher=Texas Secretary of State |accessdate=March 4, 2016 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160306105038/https://enrpages.sos.state.tx.us/public/mar01_233_state.htm |archivedate=March 6, 2016 |df= }}</ref> Farenthold polled 142,251 votes (61.7 percent) to Barrera's 88,329 (38.3 percent).<ref>{{cite web |url=http://elections.sos.state.tx.us/elchist319_state.htm|title=Election Results|date=November 8, 2016|publisher=[[Texas Secretary of State]]|accessdate=December 17, 2016}}</ref>\n\nFarenthold joined the [[Republican Study Committee]], as well as the [[Tea Party Caucus]]. Since redistricting in 2011, his district ran along the middle Texas Gulf coast from [[Corpus Christi, Texas|Corpus Christi]] to [[Bay City, Texas|Bay City]] and inland to [[Luling, Texas|Luling]], and includes [[Aransas County, Texas|Aransas]], [[Calhoun County, Texas|Calhoun]], [[Jackson County, Texas|Jackson]], [[Lavaca County, Texas|Lavaca]], [[Matagorda County, Texas|Matagorda]], [[Nueces County, Texas|Nueces]], [[Refugio County, Texas|Refugio]], [[San Patricio County, Texas|San Patricio]], [[Victoria County, Texas|Victoria]], [[Wharton County, Texas|Wharton]], and parts of [[Bastrop County, Texas|Bastrop]], [[Caldwell County, Texas|Caldwell]], and [[Gonzales County, Texas|Gonzales]] counties.\n\n==Political positions==\n\n=== Internet ===\nHaving used the Internet since the mid-1980s,<ref name=\"farenthold19851009\">{{cite web | url=http://www.columbia.edu/kermit/ftp/e/mail.85b | title=Kermit on The Source | publisher=Kermit Project, Columbia University | work=Info-Kermit Digest | date=October 9, 1985 | accessdate=February 29, 2016 | author=Farenthold, R. Blake}}</ref> Farenthold received praise from the online privacy community when he introduced bipartisan legislation that would prevent states from forcing companies to weaken encryption for law enforcement purposes.<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://arstechnica.com/tech-policy/2016/02/house-bill-would-kill-state-local-bills-that-aim-to-weaken-smartphone-crypto | title=House bill would kill state, local bills that aim to weaken smartphone crypto | website=Ars Technica | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160210135332/http://arstechnica.com/tech-policy/2016/02/house-bill-would-kill-state-local-bills-that-aim-to-weaken-smartphone-crypto/ | date=February 10, 2016 | first=Cyrus | last=Farivar | archive-date=February 10, 2016 | dead-url=no | access-date=February 10, 2016}}</ref> However, Farenthold voted to [[Congressional Review Act|repeal]] an FCC Internet privacy rule that would have prohibited [[Internet service provider]]s from selling the browsing history of their customers without customers' consent.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://austin.blog.mystatesman.com/2017/03/29/almost-every-u-s-representative-from-central-texas-voted-for-repeal-of-internet-privacy-rule/ | title=Almost every U.S. representative from Central Texas voted for repeal of Internet privacy rule | work=Austin American-Statesman | date=March 29, 2017}}</ref>\n\n=== Donald Trump ===\nFarenthold endorsed Trump in the 2016 presidential race.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news | url=https://www.dallasnews.com/news/2016-presidential-election/2016/10/11/texas-congressman-apologizes-suggesting-back-trump-even-trump-confessed-rape | title=If Trump said he really liked to rape women, would you endorse him? Maybe, says Texas lawmaker | date=October 11, 2016 | work=Dallas News | first=Jordan | last=Rudner | access-date=July 24, 2017 | language=en}}</ref> After the [[Donald Trump and Billy Bush recording]] was made public, Farenthold was asked what it would take for him to rescind his endorsement, and whether Trump saying \"I really like raping women\" would be sufficient, Farenthold said that he \"would have to consider it.\"<ref name=\":0\" /> Farenthold later apologized, saying \"I apologize for my failure to immediately condemn anyone who would say something as outrageous as they like raping women... I do not, and have not ever condoned rape or violence against women. That is not the kind of man I believe Donald Trump to be.\"<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nHe supported [[Donald Trump]]'s 2017 [[Executive Order 13769|executive order]] to impose a temporary ban on entry to the U.S. to citizens of seven Muslim-majority countries, saying \"we must be cautious who we allow into our country.\"<ref name=\"Blake1\">{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/the-fix/wp/2017/01/29/heres-where-republicans-stand-on-president-trumps-controversial-travel-ban|title=Whip Count: Here's where Republicans stand on Trump's controversial travel ban|date=January 31, 2017|last1=Blake|first1=Aaron|newspaper=Washington Post}}</ref>\n\n=== Ethics ===\nIn January 2017, Farenthold voted in favor of gutting the powers of the [[Office of Congressional Ethics]], supporting a measure that would remove the office's independence by placing it under the jurisdiction of the Republican-led [[House Ethics Committee]]. Following a backlash, the decision was reversed.<ref>{{cite news | first=John C. | last=Moritz | url=http://www.caller.com/story/news/local/texas/state-bureau/2017/01/03/farenthold-among-republicans-voting-gut-ethics-panel/96125666/ | title=Farenthold among Republicans voting to gut ethics panel | work=[[Corpus Christi Caller-Times]] | date=January 3, 2017}}</ref>\n\n=== Health care ===\nOn May 4, 2017, Farenthold voted to repeal the [[Patient Protection and Affordable Care Act]] (Obamacare) and pass the [[American Health Care Act of 2017|American Health Care Act]].<ref name=\":022\">{{cite web | url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/graphics/politics/ahca-house-vote/ | title=How the House voted to pass the GOP health-care bill | work=The Washington Post | first1=Kim | last1=Soffen | first2=Darla | last2=Cameron | first3=Kevin | last3=Uhrmacher | date= May 4, 2017 | access-date=May 4, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.cnn.com/2017/05/04/politics/house-health-care-vote/index.html | title=How every member voted on health care bill | publisher=CNN | date=May 5, 2017 | access-date=May 4, 2017}}</ref> In a radio interview in July 2017, he said it was \"absolutely repugnant\" that the [[Patient Protection and Affordable Care Act|Affordable Care Act]] had not been repealed yet. In particular, he criticized \"some female senators from the Northeast,\" and stated \"if it was a guy from south Texas, I might ask him to step outside and settle this [[Burr\u2013Hamilton duel|Aaron Burr-style]].\"<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.apnews.com/aa59b766a4294989a62c922112580af7/The-Latest:-Lawmaker-blames-female-senators-for-failed-bill|title=The Latest: Lawmaker blames female senators for failed bill|agency=Associated Press|access-date=July 24, 2017|language=en-US}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://soundcloud.com/1440-keys-corpus-christi/bob-jones-7-21-17-27th-district-congressman-blake-farenthold|title=Bob Jones 7 - 21 - 17 27th District Congressman Blake Farenthold|date=July 21, 2017|website=SoundCloud |publisher=1440 KEYS Corpus Christi|access-date=July 24, 2017}}</ref>\n\n=== 2016 election conspiracy theories ===\nIn a May 2017 appearance on CNN, Farenthold publicly doubted the [[Russian interference in the 2016 United States elections|Russian hack of Democratic Party servers]] and instead promoted a debunked [[conspiracy theory]] that the hack was an \"inside job.\" When pressed by journalist [[John Berman]], Farenthold defended his statement by saying that there were \"Things circulating on the internet.\" Farenthold's claim contradicted testimony from former [[Central Intelligence Agency]] (CIA) Director [[John O. Brennan|John Brennan]] and the conclusions of the [[Federal Bureau of Investigation]] and CIA.<ref>Chris Cillizza, [http://www.cnn.com/2017/05/24/politics/blake-farenthold-seth-rich/ A Texas Republican Congressman just said something deeply irresponsible about Seth Rich's murder], CNN (May 24, 2017).</ref><ref>Philip Bump, [https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/politics/wp/2017/05/24/another-elected-official-cites-the-internet-in-defense-of-his-bad-arguments/ Another elected official cites 'the Internet' in defense of his bad arguments], ''Washington Post'' (May 24, 2017).</ref><ref>Matt Woolbright, [http://www.caller.com/story/news/politics/2017/05/24/farenthold-dnc-staffer-killing-needs-federal-investigation/102112272/ Farenthold: DNC staffer killing needs federal investigation], ''Corpus Christi Caller-Times'' (May 24, 2017).</ref>  Farenholdt's statement was criticized by the editorial board of the ''[[Corpus Christi Caller-Times]]'', who called it \"Farenthold's latest new low\" and said \"Farenthold's antics are becoming increasingly cartoonish.\"<ref>[http://www.caller.com/story/opinion/editorials/2017/05/25/farentholds-latest-new-low-reflects-upon-his-constituents/102144968/ Editorial: Farenthold's latest new low reflects upon his constituents], ''Corpus Christi Caller-Times'' (May 25, 2017).</ref>\n\n== Lobbying career ==\nAfter resigning from Congress, Farenthold announced on May 14, 2018 that he would be serving as the [[lobbyist|legislative liaison]] for the [[Port of Port Lavaca \u2013 Point Comfort|Calhoun Port Authority]] at a salary of $160,000.10 after resigning his Congressional seat.<ref name=\"Ramirez\">{{cite news|last1=Ramirez|first1=Chris|title=Embattled ex-congressman Blake Farenthold finds safe harbor at the Port of Port Lavaca|url=https://www.caller.com/story/news/2018/05/14/ex-congressman-blake-farenthold-finds-safe-harbor-port-lavaca/600039002/|accessdate=May 15, 2018|work=Corpus Christi Caller-Times|date=May 15, 2018}}</ref> Farenthold's appointment was questioned because of the reasons for the resignation and because [[Revolving door (politics)#United States|\"Revolving Door\" laws]] generally prohibit former representatives from immediately lobbying their recent colleagues.<ref name=\"HuffPo\">{{cite news|last1=Bendery|first1=Jennifer|title=Not An Onion Story: Blake Farenthold Gets A New Job Lobbying Congress|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/entry/blake-farenthold-new-job-lobbying-congress_us_5af9e9f0e4b09a94524b26f6|accessdate=May 15, 2018|work=Huffington Post|date=May 15, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Maskell|first1=Jack|title=Post-Employment, \"Revolving Door,\" Laws for Federal Personnel|url=https://fas.org/sgp/crs/misc/R42728.pdf|website=Federation of American Scientists|publisher=Congressional Research Service|accessdate=May 15, 2018}}</ref>\n\n== Personal life ==\nFarenthold lives with his wife Debbie and two daughters Morgan and Amanda in [[Corpus Christi, Texas|Corpus Christi]].\n\nIn 1972, when Farenthold was ten years old, his father disappeared and was later found dead, his body having washed ashore after being weighed down with a cement block and deposited in [[Corpus Christi Bay]].<ref>{{cite news | title=Millionaire Slain; Found on Beach | url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=1314&dat=19720607&id=e-0vAAAAIBAJ&sjid=j-wDAAAAIBAJ&pg=3954,2965899 | accessdate=October 20, 2013 | newspaper=The Spokesman-Review | date=June 7, 1972 | agency=Associated Press | location=Spokane, Washington}}</ref> The gangland-style murder was the work of enemies of the elder Farenthold, who feared he would testify against a group of con artists who had tried to defraud him out of $100,000.<ref name=\"BloodOfFarentholds\" />\n\nIn 2010, images of Farenthold dressed in one-piece fleece \"ducky\" pajamas alongside women in lingerie emerged on the website thecrushgirls.com. Farenthold's Democratic challenger subsequently ran a political ad highlighting the unusual nature of the images.<ref>{{cite news | last1=Siegel | first1=Elyse | title=GOP Candidate Blake Farenthold Targeted After Being Caught in Ducky Pajamas With Scantily Clad Women | url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2010/10/16/blake-farenthold-pictures_n_764685.html | accessdate=December 8, 2014 | work=The Huffington Post | date=October 16, 2010}}</ref>\n\n== Allegations of inappropriate behavior ==\n\n=== Lauren Greene ===\n\nIn 2014, Farenthold was sued by a former staffer, Lauren Greene, who accused the congressman of gender discrimination, saying that he created a [[hostile work environment]] and improperly fired her after she complained.<ref>{{cite news | last1=Bresnahan | first1=John | title=Ex-spokeswoman sues Blake Farenthold, alleges discrimination | url=http://www.politico.com/story/2014/12/blake-farenthold-lawsuit-discrimination-113620.html | accessdate=December 17, 2014 | work=Politico | date=December 16, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine | title=Congressman Who Owns 'Blow-me.org' Sued for Sexual Harassment | first=Margaret | last=Hartmann | date=December 17, 2014 | url=http://nymag.com/daily/intelligencer/2014/12/blow-meorg-congressman-sued-for-harassment.html | magazine=New York Magazine}}</ref> Greene said another Farenthold aide told her the lawmaker said he had \"sexual fantasies\" and \"wet dreams\" about Greene. She also claimed that Farenthold \"regularly drank to excess\" and told her in February 2014 that he was \"estranged from his wife and had not had sex with her in years.\"<ref name=\"Politico-2017-12-01\" />\n\nWhen she complained about comments Farenthold and a male staffer made to her, Greene said the congressman improperly fired her. She filed a lawsuit in U.S. District Court in the District of Columbia, but the case was later dropped after both parties reached a private settlement.\n\nThe [[sexual harassment]] lawsuit was settled out of court in November 2015 on confidential terms.<ref>{{cite web | first=Bridget | last=Bowman | url=http://www.rollcall.com/news/home/farenthold-sexual-harassment-case-settled-court | title=Farenthold Sexual Harassment Case Is Settled Out of Court | work=Roll Call | date=November 18, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | first=Kevin | last=Diaz | url=http://www.chron.com/news/politics/article/Farenthold-settles-sexual-discrimination-suit-6643817.php | title=Farenthold settles sexual discrimination suit | work=Houston Chronicle | date=November 19, 2015}}</ref> In December 2017, it was reported that the settlement, for $84,000, was made with taxpayer money.<ref name=\"Politico-2017-12-01\" /><ref>{{cite web|last=Zielinski|first=Alex|date=January 3, 2018|title=Rep. Farenthold Said He'd Immediately Repay Taxpayers the $84k Spent on Sexual Harrassment &#91;sic&#93; Case. He Hasn't.|url=https://www.sacurrent.com/the-daily/archives/2018/01/03/rep-farenthold-said-hed-immediately-repay-taxpayers-the-84k-spent-on-sexual-harrassment-case-he-hasnt|website=SACurrent.com|publisher=San Antonio Current|access-date=January 5, 2018}}</ref>\n\n=== Michael Rekola ===\n\nIn December 2017, Michael Rekola, a former senior aide and communications director to Farenthold, alleged that the congressman was verbally abusive and sexually demeaning, and described his congressional office as an intensely hostile environment with Farenthold often making comments about women's physical features,&nbsp;including their breasts or behinds.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/entry/farenthold-verbal-abuse-sexual-remarks_us_5a31d972e4b01bdd7659dce3|title=Rep. Farenthold's Former Aide Describes Abusive Behavior In CNN Report|last=Ruiz-Grossman|first=Sarah|date=December 14, 2017|work=Huffington Post|access-date=December 14, 2017|language=en-US}}</ref> Past co-workers and relatives have corroborated Rekola's story, some having first-hand accounts of Farenthold subjecting his staff \"to a stream of angry behavior...screaming fits of rage, slamming fists on desks and castigating aides\", and regularly using profane slurs to describe those who worked in his office.<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.cnn.com/2017/12/13/politics/blake-farenthold-accusations/index.html|title=Ex-Farenthold aide shares new details of vulgar and abusive behavior|last=Reporter|first=MJ Lee, CNN National Politics|work=CNN|access-date=December 14, 2017}}</ref> Farenthold has denied the use of sexual insults lodged against him, but has admitted to the use of vulgar language, claiming that it was \"in jest\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://theweek.com/speedreads/743335/gop-rep-blake-farenthold-admits-regularly-calling-staffers-particular-vulgar-name-says-jest|title=GOP Rep. Blake Farenthold admits to regularly calling staffers one particular vulgar name, says it was 'in jest'|date=December 14, 2017|publisher=|accessdate=December 14, 2017}}</ref>\n\nFarenthold announced on December 14, 2017, that he would retire and not seek reelection to his seat in 2018.<ref name=\"quinn\">{{cite news|url=http://www.washingtonexaminer.com/blake-farenthold-to-retire-from-congress-amid-allegations-of-sexual-misconduct-abusive-behavior/article/2643484|title=Blake Farenthold to retire from Congress amid allegations of sexual misconduct, 'abusive' behavior|last=Quinn|first=Melissa|date=December 14, 2017|work=[[Washington Examiner]]|access-date=December 14, 2017|location=Washington, DC}}</ref><ref name=\"schneider\">{{cite news|url=https://www.politico.com/story/2017/12/14/farenthold-wont-seek-reelection-after-sexual-harassment-allegations-295492|title=Farenthold won't seek reelection|last=Schneider|first=Elena|date=December 14, 2017|work=[[Politico]]|access-date=December 14, 2017|location=Washington, DC}}</ref>\n\nOn April 6, 2018, he suddenly resigned from office.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/powerpost/wp/2018/04/06/rep-blake-farenthold-facing-ethics-probe-abruptly-resigns/ |title=Rep. Blake Farenthold, facing ethics probe, abruptly resigns |last=DeBonis |first=Mike |date=April 6, 2018 |website=Washington Post |language=en-US |access-date=April 6, 2018}}</ref>\n\nOn April 24, 2018, Texas Governor [[Greg Abbott|Greg Abbot]] ordered an emergency special election for the [[Texas's 27th congressional district|district]] to be held June 30, 2018. Governor Abbott requested that Farenthold pay the cost for the special election as Farenthold had failed to honor his promise to repay the $84,000 in taxpayer money used to payout the sexual harassment claims.<ref>{{cite news |last=Moritz |first=John |date= April 25, 2018|title=Gov. Abbott to Blake Farenthold: You pay the cost of the special election to replace you |url=https://www.caller.com/story/news/local/texas/state-bureau/2018/04/25/gov-abbott-blake-farenthold-you-pay-cost-special-election-replace-you/550744002/ |work=Corpus Christi Caller Times |location=Austin, Texas |access-date=April 27, 2018 }}</ref>\n\n{{Portalbar|Texas|Politics|Law|Radio|Christianity}}\n\n==Electoral history==\n{{Election box begin no change|title=2010 27th Congressional District of Texas Elections<ref name=\"TXSOS10\" />}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link no change\n  |party      = Republican Party (US)\n  |candidate  = '''Blake Farenthold\n  |votes      = 50,954\n  |percentage = 47.85}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link no change\n  |party      = Democratic Party (US)\n  |candidate  = [[Solomon Ortiz]]\n  |votes      = 50,155\n  |percentage = 47.10 }}\n{{Election box candidate with party link no change\n| candidate = Ed Mishou\n| party = Libertarian Party (US)\n| votes = 5,372\n| percentage =  5.04\n}}\n{{Election box total no change\n| votes = 106,599\n| percentage = 100.0\n}}\n{{Election box end}}\n\n{{Election box begin no change\n|title = 2012 27th Congressional District of Texas Elections<ref>{{cite web|title=Race Summary Report 2012 General Election|url=http://elections.sos.state.tx.us/elchist164_state.htm|website=Texas Secretary of State|accessdate=February 10, 2016|archiveurl=https://web